        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-02T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-02T01:00:00-05:00" n="934" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d934">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–246: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Robertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-02T13:00:00+07:00">January 2, 1946—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 3—3:38 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. According to telegram dated December 30 from Ward,<note n="2" xml:id="d934fn2">Robert S. Ward, Consul at Tihwa.</note> Chiang Ching-kuo<note n="3" xml:id="d934fn3">Son of Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek, President of the
                        National Government of the Republic of China.</note> arrived Tihwa December
                    26 and departed for Moscow December 28. (Embassy’s 2232, December 28 to Dept,
                    repeated Moscow.<note n="4" xml:id="d934fn4">
                        <ref target="frus1945v07#pg_1024">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1945, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, p. 1024</ref>.</note>) Ward says
                    negotiations are proceeding with rebels; that Liu<note n="5" xml:id="d934fn5">Liu Tse-jung, Chinese Commissioner for Foreign Affairs in Sinkiang.</note>
                    is confident of settlement and feels it may be soon, although (sent to Dept as
                    7; repeated to Moscow as 2) some local Chinese have taken umbrage at two new
                    rebel desiderata: (1) that troops brought in to put down rebellion be withdrawn
                    after settlement and (2) that secret police be disbanded.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
